\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Statistical Mechanics: Class Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
Tue, Mar, 26
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember, we're thinkin in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow\mu$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Canonical Ensemble
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Canonical ensemble ~ thermal equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 statistical definition of temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Boltzmann Factor and Boltzmann Expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{P\left(E_{1}\right)}{P\left(E_{2}\right)}=\exp\left(-\frac{\left(E_{1}-E_{2}\right)}{k_{B}T}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{Z}=\sum_{n}\exp\left(-\beta E_{n}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and from this we can derive all of the thermodynamical properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Grand Canonical Ensemble:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we're moving to the Gran Canonical Ensemble: so, as before, we're thinking
 in a system coupled with a reservoir.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bias towards higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gibbs factor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\propto\exp\left(-\beta E+\beta\mu N\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Grand Partition Function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{Z}=\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\exp\left(-\beta\left(E_{j}-N_{i}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quantum Ideal Gases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{Q}=\left(\frac{mk_{B}T}{2\pi\hbar}\right)^{3/2}\approx\left(\frac{1}{\lambda_{dB}}\right)^{3}
\]

\end_inset

Now, for a quantum gas, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\gtrsim n_{Q},\hspace{1em}T\leq T_{Q}\approx\left(\frac{2\pi\hbar}{mk_{B}T}\right)n^{2/3}
\]

\end_inset

And for atoms/molecules 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{Q}\leq10K$
\end_inset

, but electrons, neutron stars, etc, can have a uhc higher 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{Q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\gg n_{Q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T\ll T_{Q}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

degenerate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third Law: as 
\begin_inset Formula $T\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sakur Tetrode 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=k_{B}N\left[\ln\left(\frac{n_{Q}}{n}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 quantum particles indistinguishable, non-interacting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's assume that we're dealing with bosons, this, we know that the wave
 function must be symmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the contrary, if we're dealing with fermions, then, we know that the
 wave function must be antisymetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Occupancy number of a particular orbital: 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{s}\left(E_{s},T,\mu\right)$
\end_inset

, and in the classical limit 
\begin_inset Formula $f\ll1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\text{=}\left\langle n\right\rangle =k_{B}T\frac{\partial}{\partial\mu}\left(\ln\mathcal{Z}\right)=k_{B}T\frac{1}{\mathcal{Z}}\frac{\partial\mathcal{Z}}{\partial\mu}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's start with fermions: the only possible values are 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Fermi Dirac Distribution
\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{s}=\frac{1}{\exp\left(\beta\left(E_{s}-\mu\right)\right)+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Fermi Energy:
\series default
 let's consider 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset


\series bold
 
\series default
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(T=0\right)$
\end_inset


\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{n}=\frac{\hbar^{2}\pi^{2}}{2mL^{2}}n^{2},
\]

\end_inset


\series default
for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{max}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the Fermi energy, and from this we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N=2\frac{1}{8}\frac{4\pi}{3}n_{max}^{3}\implies n_{max}^{3}=\frac{3}{\pi}N,
\]

\end_inset

and from this 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{F}=\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\left(3\pi n\right)^{2/3},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Density of States: number of orbitals with 
\begin_inset Formula $E<E\left(n\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{0}\left(n\right)=\frac{\pi}{3}n^{3},
\]

\end_inset

and from this we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dN_{0}}{dn}=\pi n^{2},
\]

\end_inset

but I want to know 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dN_{0}}{dE}=\frac{dN_{0}}{dn}\frac{dn}{dE},
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=\left(\frac{2mL^{2}}{\hbar^{2}\pi^{2}}E\right)^{1/2},
\]

\end_inset

and from this we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dN_{0}}{dE}=\frac{V}{2\pi^{2}}\left(\frac{2m}{\hbar^{2}}\right)^{\frac{3}{2}}E^{\frac{1}{2}},
\]

\end_inset

and from this we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D\left(E\right)=\frac{3}{2}\left(\frac{N}{E_{F}}\right)\left(\frac{E}{E_{F}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
